    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>In the Mideast, a Bridge Too Far</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jack S Berger letter, commenting on former Pres Jimmy Carter's August 6 Op-Ed article, blames deadlock in Middle East peace efforts on Palestinian intransigence</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Jerusalem Settlement Everyone Can Live With,'' by Jimmy Carter (Op-Ed, Aug. 6):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''A Jerusalem Settlement Everyone Can Live With,'' by Jimmy Carter (Op-Ed, Aug. 6):</p>
        <p>While former President Carter's call for a semblance of neutrality is reasonable, the current pronouncements from Washington do reveal an important issue: an intransigence of heart by the Palestinian Authority.</p>
        <p>Good faith on both sides requires that they implicitly accept the existence of the other as a fact of life. Notwithstanding the prevailing lip service, the Palestinian Authority has not crossed the bridge to make this concession.</p>
        <p>A meeting of minds will remain elusive so long as the Palestinian side offers cant but trains its young in the murder and abduction of its Israeli counterparts.</p>
        <p>JACK S. BERGER  Mahwah, N.J., Aug. 6, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
